      <h1>How to Negotiate Salary in the US: Scripts, Timing and Tactics</h1>
      <div class="article-meta"><span>Jun 14, 2025</span><span>·</span><span>8 min read</span></div>
      <p class="article-intro">Studies show 73% of employers expect salary negotiation — but only 37% of workers negotiate every time. Here's how to be in the 37% who consistently earn more.</p>
    </div>
  </div>
  <div class="container" style="max-width:740px;">
    <div class="prose">
      <div class="callout"><strong>Before you negotiate:</strong> Know your exact numbers. Use our <a href="/">hourly to salary calculator</a> to understand your current rate and target.</div>

      <h2>When to negotiate salary</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>New job offer:</strong> Always negotiate. The offer is never final. Employers expect it.</li>
        <li><strong>Annual review:</strong> Best time to ask for a raise. Come prepared with achievements.</li>
        <li><strong>Promotion:</strong> Negotiate the new salary separately from the promotion itself.</li>
        <li><strong>Counter-offer:</strong> If you have another offer, use it as leverage.</li>
        <li><strong>After a major win:</strong> Strike when you've just delivered visible results.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>How much to ask for</h2>
      <p>Research your market rate first. Check Glassdoor, Levels.fyi (for tech), LinkedIn Salary, and the Bureau of Labor Statistics. Then:</p>
      <ul>
        <li>Entry level: Ask for 5–10% above offer</li>
        <li>Mid level: Ask for 10–15% above offer</li>
        <li>Senior/specialized: Ask for 15–25% above offer</li>
        <li>For annual raises: Ask for 8–15% (inflation + merit)</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Salary negotiation scripts</h2>

      <h3>Script 1: Responding to an offer</h3>
      <p>"Thank you so much for the offer — I'm genuinely excited about this role. Based on my research into market rates for this position in [city], and given my [X years of experience / specific skill], I was expecting something closer to $[X]. Is there flexibility to get to that number?"</p>

      <h3>Script 2: Asking for a raise</h3>
      <p>"I'd like to discuss my compensation. Over the past year, I've [specific achievement 1] and [specific achievement 2], which resulted in [measurable outcome]. Given my contributions and the current market rate for my role, I'm hoping we can adjust my salary to $[X]. What would it take to make that happen?"</p>

      <h3>Script 3: When they say no</h3>
      <p>"I understand. Can you help me understand what I'd need to achieve to get to $[X], and what timeline we're talking about? I'd also like to explore whether there's flexibility on [signing bonus / extra PTO / remote work / equity]."</p>

      <h2>Negotiation mistakes to avoid</h2>
      <ul>
        <li><strong>Giving a range:</strong> They'll always pick the bottom. Give one specific number.</li>
        <li><strong>Anchoring low:</strong> Your first number sets the ceiling. Start higher than your target.</li>
        <li><strong>Apologizing:</strong> Never say "I'm sorry to ask but..." — it signals weakness.</li>
        <li><strong>Accepting verbally on the spot:</strong> Always say "let me think about it" and respond in writing.</li>
        <li><strong>Only negotiating base:</strong> Total comp includes bonus, equity, PTO, remote flexibility, 401k match.</li>
      </ul>

      <h2>Beyond base salary: What else to negotiate</h2>
      <ul>
        <li>Signing bonus (especially valuable if leaving unvested equity)</li>
        <li>Annual bonus target (ask for % in writing)</li>
        <li>Equity / RSUs (ask for vesting schedule and refresh policy)</li>
        <li>Extra PTO days (often easier to get than salary)</li>
        <li>Remote work flexibility</li>
        <li>401k match vesting schedule</li>
        <li>Professional development budget</li>
        <li>Title (affects future earning power)</li>
      </ul>

